Foreign parts still account for 56% of the value of Thailand’s car exports, according to the most recent data from the World Trade Organisation ( WTO ).
Thailand’s cosmopolitan car industry illustrates the potential of “global value chains”, which link several countries in the production of a good or service.
Unfortunately, these chains declined relative to world GDP between 2011 and 2016, contributing to what has been dubbed “slowbalisation”.
Ties that bindMeanwhile, the political salience of value chains has shot up, thanks to tax battles and trade wars.
As a result, many commentators (including this newspaper on occasion) have claimed that 60% of world trade takes place within multinational firms.